{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13139"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13139"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0,0.31,0.01,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116272"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116272"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a motor vehicle collision. He is unresponsive with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 6. He has shallow, laboured breathing with an oxygen saturation of 88% on room air. He has an open fracture of the right femur. On examination, there are no obvious signs of external bleeding, but there is decreased breath sounds on the left side of the chest. There is no tracheal deviation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate blood transfusion","Closed reduction of the femur fracture","Needle decompression of the chest","Insertion of a central line","Endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation of altered mental status (Glasgow Coma Scale score \u22648), hypoxia, and laboured breathing is indicative of significant head injury or inadequate oxygenation and ventilation, which requires immediate airway management via \u003Cstrong\u003Eendotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E. This intervention is crucial to ensure adequate oxygen delivery to vital organs, especially the brain. His current oxygen saturation of 88% is also of concern and adds support to the need for immediate endotracheal intubation and mechanical ventilation. Certainly the resuscitation team would be very much aware of the possibility of an underlying pneumothorax and the need for rapid decompression if the situation worsened.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate blood transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for a trauma patient with signs of haemorrhagic shock, which this patient does not exhibit. \u003Cstrong\u003EClosed reduction of the femur fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is not an immediate priority given the patient\u0027s respiratory and neurological status. \u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle decompression\u003C/strong\u003E or a chest tube may be required for further management of this patient, as unilateral decreased breath sounds in a trauma patient may indicate an underlying haemothorax or pneumothorax. However, in this case the airway would still take precedence as no other signs of tension pneumothorax are present. \u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of a central line\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly not the first priority when compared to securing the airway in this patient\u0027s situation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Airway management is the first priority (A of ABC - Airway, Breathing, Circulation) in the primary survey of trauma patients.","Any patient with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of \u22648 should be intubated to protect the airway and ensure adequate oxygenation and ventilation."],"references":["Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) Student Course Manual (10th Edition), American College of Surgeons, Chicago 2018.","Carney N, Totten AM, O\u0027Reilly C, et al. Guidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury, Fourth Edition. Neurosurgery. 2017;80(1):6-15."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13139"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T07:29:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:29:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116272"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1493"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Traumatic brain injury","synonyms":["TBI","Head injury","Concussion"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-12-17T09:54:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T09:07:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"con